- Hmm.

17:20.137 --> 17:21.472
That's very kind.

17:22.373 --> 17:23.674
It's all right.

17:27.511 --> 17:29.248
You're very special, Julie.

17:30.647 --> 17:32.448
I don't think I am.

17:32.450 --> 17:34.816
Oh, no, you don't
think you are.

17:34.818 --> 17:38.386
- Very normal, really.
- Yeah, normal.

17:38.388 --> 17:41.559
You're not normal at all.
You're a freak.

17:42.559 --> 17:44.062
Thank you.

17:48.199 --> 17:50.402
- How am I a freak?
- Your fragility.

17:53.570 --> 17:55.638
Is that a good thing?

17:55.640 --> 17:57.176
I think you know.

17:58.143 --> 17:59.577
I think I'm quite average.

18:01.546 --> 18:03.082
You're not average.

18:07.585 --> 18:09.121
You're lost.

18:10.454 --> 18:12.191
And you'll
always be lost.

18:24.469 --> 18:26.238
(OPERA MUSIC PLAYING)

18:34.846 --> 18:37.281
- Are you hungry?
- ANTHONY: Famished.

18:38.549 --> 18:39.748
How did you get on?

18:39.750 --> 18:41.551
Really well,
thank you.

18:41.553 --> 18:44.286
- Good old Harrods?
- Yeah.

18:44.288 --> 18:46.625
- A nice bit of fillet steak.
- ANTHONY: Hmm.

18:48.625 --> 18:50.461
I've had
a very nice time here.

18:50.761 --> 18:52.163
Good.

18:52.663 --> 18:54.363
Very relaxing.

18:54.365 --> 18:55.634
Good.

18:57.234 --> 18:59.770
Checked in on Janet.
Everything's fine there.

19:00.837 --> 19:02.374
Good.

19:04.474 --> 19:07.709
I mean, I dare say
they've had

19:07.711 --> 19:12.215
the odd person,
uh, watching over,

19:12.217 --> 19:15.450
but I don't think
there's been any disturbance.

19:15.452 --> 19:17.886
Hmm. I'm glad.

19:17.888 --> 19:19.622
That's partly
why I wanted to get Ray

19:19.624 --> 19:21.289
out of there
for the weekend.

19:21.291 --> 19:22.792
REPORTER: (OVER RADIO)
<i>There were fears</i>

19:22.794 --> 19:24.326
<i>that the Russians
might try to come in</i>

19:24.328 --> 19:26.429
<i>and slew the submarine
off the rocks,</i>

19:26.431 --> 19:27.830
<i>and those fears
were reinforced</i>

19:27.832 --> 19:29.765
<i>when a second
foreign submarine</i>

19:29.767 --> 19:31.767
<i>was detected
earlier this morning.</i>

19:31.769 --> 19:33.869
<i>Today, the government revealed
that they're considering</i>

19:33.871 --> 19:36.271
<i>a charge of espionage.</i>

19:36.273 --> 19:37.606
<i>The case is seen
as very similar</i>

19:37.608 --> 19:39.275
<i>to that of Gary Powers,</i>

19:39.277 --> 19:41.611
<i>the American pilot
of a U-2 spy plane</i>

19:41.613 --> 19:44.447
<i>shot down over Russia in 1960.</i>

19:44.449 --> 19:46.716
<i>The Russians
tried him as a spy.</i>

19:46.718 --> 19:48.720
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING ON RADIO)

20:19.916 --> 20:21.720
(BELL TOLLING)

20:26.490 --> 20:28.958
JULIE: <i>"You've got to
see Venice," he began.</i>

20:28.960 --> 20:31.294
"You've got to see
a city of slender towers

20:31.296 --> 20:32.862
"and white domes,

20:32.864 --> 20:35.701
"sleeping in the water
like a mass of water lilies.

20:36.933 --> 20:38.968
"You've got to see
dark waterways,

20:38.970 --> 20:41.069
"mysterious threads of shadow,

20:41.071 --> 20:43.875
"binding all these flowers
of stone together."

21:18.843 --> 21:20.379
JULIE: I like this.

21:28.452 --> 21:29.884
And where was
this taken?

21:29.886 --> 21:32.923
- Afghanistan. '73.
- Oh.

21:41.732 --> 21:43.501
I'm going to
wash the lettuce.

21:52.643 --> 21:54.744
JULIE: "I don't feel
that I fully understand

21:54.746 --> 21:56.679
"the qualities
of entertainment,

21:56.681 --> 21:59.047
"but I realize the importance
of entertaining people

21:59.049 --> 22:00.949
"to get a message across.

22:00.951 --> 22:04.120
"I hope to learn to entertain
as well as communicate."

22:04.122 --> 22:06.421
- That's good.
- Yeah.

22:06.423 --> 22:08.693
That's the bit I like,
at the end.

22:10.027 --> 22:12.795
What's all that
about therapy?

22:12.797 --> 22:15.534
Well, it's my version
of therapy, really.

22:16.500 --> 22:19.104
- Okay.
- My self-expression.

22:20.771 --> 22:24.140
Through art, through film,
you know, that's my...

22:24.142 --> 22:26.411
Do you think
that makes you special?

22:27.144 --> 22:28.710
Well, it's not,
you know...

22:28.712 --> 22:30.746
It's not about me
being special.

22:30.748 --> 22:33.485
It's about, you know,
them, you know...

22:37.989 --> 22:41.157
It's just, I want them
to know that...

22:41.159 --> 22:44.459
I want them to kind of know
that about me, you know?

22:44.461 --> 22:45.960
- Okay. Okay.
- Is that...

22:45.962 --> 22:48.029
- Do you think it's too...
- No.

22:48.031 --> 22:51.534
I'm not sure, uh,
sincerity is always enough.

22:51.536 --> 22:53.701
But go on.
Let's hear the next bit.

22:53.703 --> 22:56.471
Okay. You mean...

22:56.473 --> 22:59.074
You mean you don't think
I should be this honest?

22:59.076 --> 23:04.013
Um, well, no, I just think
it's, um, you know...

23:04.015 --> 23:07.816
People use that word
as if it's an end in itself,

23:07.818 --> 23:12.555
and, uh, I mean, you know,
we can all be sincere,

23:12.557 --> 23:15.958
we can all
be authentic,

23:15.960 --> 23:18.563
but, um,
what's it all for?

23:23.201 --> 23:25.534
I mean, it just
slightly reads

23:25.536 --> 23:30.475
like you've been sort of
backed into a corner by life,

23:30.907 --> 23:32.208
and it's like,

23:32.210 --> 23:35.210
"Oh, well, I'd better be
a film director."

23:35.212 --> 23:37.479
As opposed to,
"I want to be a film director."

23:37.481 --> 23:39.113
Is that what
it sounds like?

23:39.115 --> 23:41.249
What happened last night

23:41.251 --> 23:46.023
is every time you rolled over
and then rolled back again,

23:47.758 --> 23:53.531
you came closer to me
and took up more of the bed.

23:55.232 --> 23:58.234
And you're already,
I would say,

23:58.236 --> 23:59.838
further over than I am.

24:02.272 --> 24:03.873
That's not true.

24:03.875 --> 24:05.740
- It is true.
- No, it's not.

24:05.742 --> 24:09.111
- I haven't got that much...
- You have bed dysmorphia.

24:09.113 --> 24:10.946
(LAUGHS)

24:10.948 --> 24:13.148
And you...
Then you accuse me of...

24:13.150 --> 24:16.988
I wasn't trying to cross
any sort of threshold.

24:19.656 --> 24:21.623
(CHUCKLES)

24:21.625 --> 24:23.225
I have not got
that much room.

24:23.227 --> 24:26.163
You've got a foot
on that side.

24:26.998 --> 24:28.229
That's not a foot.

24:28.231 --> 24:29.768
And I literally
am on a ledge.

24:32.103 --> 24:35.039
- I've got nowhere left to go.
- (LAUGHING)

24:38.742 --> 24:41.709
Well, where's the...
Where's the halfway line?

24:41.711 --> 24:43.045
Well, I think
it's where your arm is,

24:43.047 --> 24:44.580
but, like, under your arm.

24:44.582 --> 24:45.980
No, I think it's there.

24:45.982 --> 24:48.984
No, I think it's,
like, there.

24:48.986 --> 24:51.886
No. That doesn't
give me enough room.

24:51.888 --> 24:54.155
- There.
- All right, there.

24:54.157 --> 24:58.026
But I can barely
lie flat like that.

24:58.028 --> 24:59.761
We're saying there, okay.

24:59.763 --> 25:03.332
I'm going to do
a Claudette Colbert,

25:03.334 --> 25:07.005
Clark Gable, wall of Jericho

25:08.306 --> 25:09.774
with your friends here.

25:10.273 --> 25:12.607
(LAUGHING)

25:12.609 --> 25:14.677
I haven't got much room.

25:14.679 --> 25:16.844
- You've got a foot!
- (LAUGHING)

25:16.846 --> 25:18.849
You've got a foot.
I have nothing.

25:21.117 --> 25:23.153
I've nothing.
There's nothing here.

25:31.328 --> 25:33.197
(ELEVATOR DOOR OPENS)

25:49.113 --> 25:51.249
I'm going to be in Paris
for a while.

25:54.184 --> 25:55.720
Okay.

25:57.922 --> 25:59.257
See you soon.

26:07.230 --> 26:08.767
(ELEVATOR DOOR CLOSES)

26:14.638 --> 26:16.705
JULIE: <i>"My dear Julie.</i>

26:16.707 --> 26:18.176
<i>"Just a letter of thanks.</i>

26:19.242 --> 26:20.409
<i>"You see,
I've almost forgotten</i>

26:20.411 --> 26:22.080
<i>"what happened in December.</i>

26:23.847 --> 26:26.649
<i>"I may have been born in 1980,</i>

26:26.651 --> 26:29.951
<i>"and that was the year
I first fell in love.</i>

26:29.953 --> 26:32.222
<i>"And I have wondered
if that were possible.</i>

26:33.891 --> 26:35.927
<i>"I have gained so much
to thank you for.</i>

26:36.727 --> 26:38.160
<i>"Inexpressible, though,</i>

26:38.162 --> 26:40.030
<i>"this thing
of delight and trust.</i>

26:41.932 --> 26:44.866
<i>"Most importantly
and at the center</i>

26:44.868 --> 26:47.135
<i>"is that I am mainly
thanking you</i>

26:47.137 --> 26:48.372
<i>"for my love for you.</i>

26:49.940 --> 26:52.074
<i>"Ergo sum.</i>

26:52.076 --> 26:54.211
<i>"A grateful
and loving Anthony."</i>

26:55.346 --> 26:57.615
(ALTERNATIVE MUSIC PLAYING)

27:27.478 --> 27:29.411
Is this my book?

27:29.413 --> 27:32.182
- Oh, yeah. Sorry.
- You... You keep it.

27:35.920 --> 27:38.256
All right. Cheers.

27:40.090 --> 27:42.290
- All right.
- Do you want a hand?

27:42.292 --> 27:43.758
FRANKIE: Yeah,
I'd better get downstairs.

27:43.760 --> 27:45.230
Jack's got
the van, ain't he?

27:47.097 --> 27:49.832
- I might torch this.
- (JULIE LAUGHS)

27:49.834 --> 27:52.301
- You give my love to Tracy.
- Yeah, I will.

27:52.303 --> 27:53.838
Yeah.

27:54.872 --> 27:56.708
- Love you, Frank.
- Love you, too.

27:57.208 --> 27:59.009
- Have fun.
- I will.

28:00.076 --> 28:01.913
- See you on the flip side.
- (CHUCKLES)

28:04.815 --> 28:06.014
(ELEVATOR DOOR OPENS)

28:06.016 --> 28:07.815
- FRANKIE: Ta-ta.
- Bye.

28:07.817 --> 28:09.220
(ELEVATOR DOOR CLOSES)

28:11.454 --> 28:14.489
The, uh...
The thing that struck me

28:14.491 --> 28:17.492
about the main character,
Tony, in my story,

28:17.494 --> 28:20.895
is that he is being forced
to rate, to be raised,

28:20.897 --> 28:26.869
and to come to terms
with the incredible struggles

28:26.871 --> 28:29.171
that his family is
going through at that time,

28:29.173 --> 28:32.874
and all his peers
at school as well.

28:32.876 --> 28:37.145
And this very cruel,

28:37.147 --> 28:42.151
very raw, you know... Um...

28:42.153 --> 28:46.188
Sorry, I'm not expressing
myself very well. Um...

28:46.190 --> 28:48.257
You know, being forced
to come to terms

28:48.259 --> 28:50.225
with something so harsh

28:50.227 --> 28:52.393
for someone that's so young.

28:52.395 --> 28:53.996
- Very vulnerable.
- Right.

28:53.998 --> 28:56.864
And yet, you're wanting
to make a film

28:56.866 --> 29:00.835
about an experience that's
very different from yours.

29:00.837 --> 29:03.372
I mean, you could argue
that really

29:03.374 --> 29:05.007
it would be
much better for you

29:05.009 --> 29:06.874
to work
from your own experience,

29:06.876 --> 29:09.143
particularly
at an early stage.

29:09.145 --> 29:12.314
I mean, what makes you
want to leave

29:12.316 --> 29:14.850
your own experience
so radically

29:14.852 --> 29:16.852
and enter into this
very different world?

29:16.854 --> 29:18.987
I mean, it's suggested
that you almost have

29:18.989 --> 29:21.957
a kind of moral,
sort of political aim?

29:21.959 --> 29:24.192
- I mean, can you just...
- JULIE: Very moral, to me.

29:24.194 --> 29:25.960
...talk about that,
perhaps, for a moment?

29:25.962 --> 29:27.496
Yes, uh...

29:27.498 --> 29:31.999
I feel as though I want to
not live my whole life

29:32.001 --> 29:37.338
in this very privileged
part of the world I come from,

29:37.340 --> 29:39.307
uh, part of the country.

29:39.309 --> 29:43.211
And I want to be really aware

29:43.213 --> 29:45.380
about what's going on
around me,

29:45.382 --> 29:51.186
with people, and community,
and politically as well.

29:51.188 --> 29:55.193
Um, I don't want to be
in that bubble my entire life.

30:03.500 --> 30:06.304
- Where's the wall?
- The wall is...

30:07.438 --> 30:09.507
The wall was.
It is no more.

30:10.974 --> 30:13.642
- We dismantled it.
- Ah.

30:13.644 --> 30:15.978
There was a whole ceremony.
You missed it.

30:15.980 --> 30:18.916
- I'm sorry I missed that.
- We all felt very snubbed.

30:20.917 --> 30:22.519
- Is this for me?
- Mmm-hmm.

30:24.020 --> 30:26.023
- Thank you.
- From Paris.

30:29.660 --> 30:31.196
Put it on.

30:32.429 --> 30:34.132
(OPERA MUSIC PLAYING)

30:41.305 --> 30:43.208
(MUSIC CONTINUES)

31:49.573 --> 31:51.009
(ANTHONY MOANING)

31:55.679 --> 31:57.982
ANTHONY:
You're a dark horse, Julie.

32:00.183 --> 32:01.385
(MOANS)

32:05.388 --> 32:07.024
I love pale skin.

32:09.660 --> 32:11.994
Why? Why?

32:11.996 --> 32:14.265
'Cause everyone's
getting a tan nowadays.

32:15.566 --> 32:18.232
- But I burn.
- Good.

32:18.234 --> 32:19.536
(CHUCKLES)

32:20.570 --> 32:22.205
We'll keep you
out the sun.

32:25.342 --> 32:26.678
I like freckles.

32:47.030 --> 32:48.796
Did you hurt yourself?

32:48.798 --> 32:50.535
No, I don't know
what that is.

32:52.536 --> 32:54.201
It looks really sore.

32:54.203 --> 32:55.539
It is a bit sore.

32:57.407 --> 32:58.640
Okay.

32:58.642 --> 32:59.677
What do you think
I should do?

33:01.377 --> 33:02.980
I think you should

33:04.748 --> 33:07.585
just leave it

33:08.384 --> 33:10.117
and let it go away.

33:10.119 --> 33:11.755
(OPERA MUSIC PLAYING)

34:07.577 --> 34:09.813
- ANTHONY: I'm going out.
- Okay.

34:10.681 --> 34:12.545
ANTHONY: I'll be back later.

34:12.547 --> 34:14.282
- See you later.
- ANTHONY: What?

34:14.284 --> 34:15.619
See you later.

34:24.628 --> 34:27.295
Can you lend me
a couple of quid?

34:27.297 --> 34:29.599
- Yeah, sure.
- Thank you.

34:32.469 --> 34:35.139
- How much?
- Uh...

34:36.739 --> 34:38.273
Six.

34:38.275 --> 34:40.342
Have you got ten?
Give me ten.

34:40.344 --> 34:41.846
Won't need ten,
but, uh,

34:43.547 --> 34:45.181
just in case.

34:53.523 --> 34:55.292
- Bye.
- Bye.

35:09.505 --> 35:11.442
(CAR HORN HONKING)

35:21.485 --> 35:23.454
I thought we'd put
Anthony down the end.

35:24.253 --> 35:26.220
Be more comfortable.

35:26.222 --> 35:28.558
It's not that kind of
relationship anyway, is it?

35:29.693 --> 35:31.659
(DOG BARKS)

35:31.661 --> 35:33.663
He's got
his own bathroom, and...

35:35.898 --> 35:39.170
He'd be
quite comfy there.

35:40.971 --> 35:43.240
Yes. That feels good.

35:45.608 --> 35:47.144
- Rosie.
- (DOG BARKS)

35:48.244 --> 35:52.746
Mummy, can I borrow
some money, please?

35:52.748 --> 35:54.548
- More money?
- Yes.

35:54.550 --> 35:55.916
Oh.

35:55.918 --> 35:57.686
(STAMMERS)
It's for college, you know.

35:57.688 --> 36:00.487
- It's for cameras and...
- It's not long since the last.

36:00.489 --> 36:02.389
- I know.
- Hmm.

36:02.391 --> 36:03.858
And I know I haven't
paid that back yet.

36:03.860 --> 36:06.931
- How much this time?
- £200.

36:08.264 --> 36:09.599
Oh, another one.

36:11.668 --> 36:14.568
- All right.
- It's just for equipment.

36:14.570 --> 36:17.338
- For film school, you know.
- Ah. Ah.

36:17.340 --> 36:18.740
Are you
keeping a tally?

36:18.742 --> 36:20.342
Yeah, of course.

36:20.344 --> 36:23.577
All right.
All right, well, yeah.

36:23.579 --> 36:25.782
- I will pay you back.
- All right. All right.

36:28.351 --> 36:29.786
(DOG WHINING)

36:32.521 --> 36:35.322
- (DOG BARKING)
- ROSALIND: Rosie! Rose!

36:35.324 --> 36:38.626
Well, we didn't really mix
with King's much, but...

36:38.628 --> 36:41.630
I think all the colleges
kept themselves to themselves.

36:41.632 --> 36:42.998
In my day.
They probably don't...

36:43.000 --> 36:44.365
- Didn't when you were there.
- Yeah, no, no.

36:44.367 --> 36:45.503
Absolutely, yes.

36:46.369 --> 36:48.269
I studied history of art

36:48.271 --> 36:49.737
and then continued
at the Courtauld.

36:49.739 --> 36:51.338
It was a funny time then,
'cause it was just

36:51.340 --> 36:53.474
- after the war, so...
- Uh-huh.

36:53.476 --> 36:56.411
I suppose it was
rather different in your day.

36:56.413 --> 36:57.778
Hmm... Well,
I don't know.

36:57.780 --> 36:59.014
ROSALIND: I think we're off.
I think we're off.

36:59.016 --> 37:00.581
We're ready for lunch.
Come on through.

37:00.583 --> 37:02.784
- Hmm. Jolly good.
- ROSALIND: Do come through.

37:02.786 --> 37:03.985
Julie, darling, can you just

37:03.987 --> 37:05.822
- come and help me?
- Yes.

37:07.056 --> 37:09.691
Starting on the wine,
I suppose.

37:09.693 --> 37:11.760
WILLIAM: Hopefully.
Yep, I think we've got

37:11.762 --> 37:13.564
a nice bottle
of something there.

37:14.931 --> 37:16.030
- ANTHONY: Through here?
- No, straight on.

37:16.032 --> 37:17.565
Straight ahead.

37:17.567 --> 37:19.066
Got to get over
the barrier, though.

37:19.068 --> 37:20.534
It's a rather
curious tradition

37:20.536 --> 37:21.836
we have in this house.

37:21.838 --> 37:23.537
It's meant
to keep the dogs out,

37:23.539 --> 37:25.509
but actually it keeps
people out.

37:32.315 --> 37:34.816
I think a lot of them
are young men

37:34.818 --> 37:37.385
who were dragged
from their beds

37:37.387 --> 37:38.653
at the crack of dawn,

37:38.655 --> 37:42.356
with little
or no hard evidence

37:42.358 --> 37:43.793
to say that they were

37:44.994 --> 37:47.330
what we would consider

37:49.365 --> 37:50.501
criminals.

37:51.768 --> 37:54.369
I don't think
granting these men

37:54.371 --> 37:58.340
political status
is such a big deal.

37:58.342 --> 38:03.778
We don't know that
they're necessarily affiliated

38:03.780 --> 38:06.680
with the exact
same organization

38:06.682 --> 38:10.918
who put bombs under cars
and shoot prison wardens

38:10.920 --> 38:14.488
while they're going about
their everyday lives.

38:14.490 --> 38:16.360
It's terribly complicated.

38:17.126 --> 38:18.659
WILLIAM: Complicated?

38:18.661 --> 38:20.994
But we've got to
protect society, haven't we?

38:20.996 --> 38:24.599
But they're just as much part
of society as anybody else,

38:24.601 --> 38:26.133
that's what they would say.

38:26.135 --> 38:27.901
And, uh, do you...

38:27.903 --> 38:30.505
WILLIAM: Well, I haven't set
any bombs recently. Have you?

38:30.507 --> 38:32.807
No, but you haven't
necessarily felt the need to,

38:32.809 --> 38:36.411
'cause you've felt that
you have a political voice.

38:36.413 --> 38:37.447
ANTHONY: Mmm-hmm.

38:38.681 --> 38:41.451
Or, or am I wrong
about that?

38:42.786 --> 38:44.418
I think you're
wrong, really,

38:44.420 --> 38:45.954
if you don't mind
my saying so.

38:45.956 --> 38:48.858
I think... I'm amazed to
hear you say this, but, um...

38:49.893 --> 38:51.726
It's refreshing
to hear this.

38:51.728 --> 38:52.994
WILLIAM: I'm quite sure

38:52.996 --> 38:55.563
they're not
all guilty as charged.

38:55.565 --> 38:58.999
But I'm sure
the majority of them are.

38:59.001 --> 39:00.534
Some of them
are proven guilty,

39:00.536 --> 39:02.839
some are not. Um...

39:04.541 --> 39:08.008
But can we risk having
bombs, pipe bombs,

39:08.010 --> 39:09.677
all sorts of foul things

39:09.679 --> 39:12.414
that are going on
all over Northern Ireland?

39:12.416 --> 39:14.115
- Can we allow that?
- ANTHONY: I'm not an apologist.

39:14.117 --> 39:15.617
Darling.

39:15.619 --> 39:16.885
WILLIAM: And if we lock up
a few innocents

39:16.887 --> 39:19.887
in the process,
well, that's part of it.

39:19.889 --> 39:21.991
- I'm not an apologist...
- No, thank you, darling.

39:23.559 --> 39:26.463
...for violence
on either side.

39:29.199 --> 39:30.800
And it is on both.

39:32.202 --> 39:34.635
WILLIAM: And what, is that
a Foreign Office view,

39:34.637 --> 39:36.037
or is that your view?

39:36.039 --> 39:38.206
Probably not, no.
That's my view.

39:38.208 --> 39:40.508
WILLIAM: That looks rather
like my cap you're wearing.

39:40.510 --> 39:42.677
- JULIE: It is your cap.
- I thought it was.

39:42.679 --> 39:44.512
It looks better
on me, I think.

39:44.514 --> 39:45.746
Yeah. I want that back.

39:45.748 --> 39:46.817
ROSALIND: You might lose that.

39:47.516 --> 39:49.018
(DOG BARKING)

39:52.088 --> 39:53.657
WILLIAM: Dog's all right.

39:56.626 --> 39:58.662
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATION)

40:30.025 --> 40:31.995
ROSALIND: (HIGH-PITCHED VOICE)
Rosie! Come!

40:33.630 --> 40:34.965
- Dora!
- JULIE: Dora!

40:36.199 --> 40:38.034
ROSALIND: Rosie! Come on!

40:44.807 --> 40:46.139
JULIE: My godfather
gave it to me.

40:46.141 --> 40:47.508
ANTHONY: Little swallow.

40:47.510 --> 40:48.976
- JULIE: Yeah.
- It's charming.

40:48.978 --> 40:51.514
JULIE: Thank you. I never...
I never wear it.

40:52.715 --> 40:55.552
But it's time for it to...

40:56.186 --> 40:57.788
Its first flight.

40:58.221 --> 40:59.556
(CHUCKLES)

41:05.228 --> 41:06.793
ANTHONY: Yeah,
it looks good there.

41:06.795 --> 41:08.231
JULIE: Hmm? Okay.

41:15.838 --> 41:19.907
It's the ultimate form,
because it's maximum cinema.

41:19.909 --> 41:23.980
It's movement, music,
energy, color.

41:25.014 --> 41:27.916
Everything
that film should be.

41:27.918 --> 41:31.052
And there's never been a good
musical made in Britain,

41:31.054 --> 41:32.320
I don't think.

41:32.322 --> 41:34.923
I mean, there's been
some Cliff Richard.

41:34.925 --> 41:36.557
- Mmm-hmm.
- PATRICK: You know,

41:36.559 --> 41:39.026
<i>Knees Up Mother Brown,</i>
whatever, but, you know,

41:39.028 --> 41:41.095
for a country
that has the Stones,

41:41.097 --> 41:42.963
The Kinks, Small Faces,

41:42.965 --> 41:47.601
for there not to be
a good musical here is just...

41:47.603 --> 41:49.105
- It's almost impressive.
- Mmm. I'd say.

41:50.106 --> 41:51.271
ANTHONY: Julie met a load of

41:51.273 --> 41:53.740
your old Raynham lot
the other day.

41:53.742 --> 41:55.275
- LYDIA: Mmm?
- PATRICK: Mmm.

41:55.277 --> 41:58.211
ANTHONY: Sounded rather
a humorless bunch.

41:58.213 --> 42:00.882
I don't know if you'd have
known any of them.

42:00.884 --> 42:02.552
Do you remember their names?

42:03.987 --> 42:06.220
No, I can't, I'm afraid.
I was so nervous.

42:06.222 --> 42:09.356
Well, it's only confidence

42:09.358 --> 42:12.159
because the whole thing
is a con.

42:12.161 --> 42:13.827
JULIE: Hmm.

42:13.829 --> 42:15.829
And they're the biggest
con artists out there

42:15.831 --> 42:17.599
who are in film school.

42:17.601 --> 42:22.135
I just used it as a kind of
supply center, really.

42:22.137 --> 42:24.072
ANTHONY: Are you glad
you went at all?

42:24.074 --> 42:25.807
PATRICK: It's the cheapest

42:25.809 --> 42:28.742
camera-hire place
in the world.

42:28.744 --> 42:30.612
I mean, they don't lock
the store cupboard.

42:30.614 --> 42:33.250
You go in there,
get the camera,

42:34.351 --> 42:38.353
and, you know,
I made two features

42:38.355 --> 42:42.155
while I was there
for, I mean, no money.

42:42.157 --> 42:44.161
They don't check
the stock, really.

42:45.362 --> 42:47.729
Couple of trims.
I mean, it's great.

42:47.731 --> 42:49.229
You have to listen
to a lot of people

42:49.231 --> 42:51.134
who think they
know about film

42:52.268 --> 42:53.767
telling you
how to make a film.

42:53.769 --> 42:55.369
It's like telling someone

42:55.371 --> 42:58.972
how to breathe
or how to think or...

42:58.974 --> 43:00.842
- ANTHONY: Yeah.
- It's ridiculous.

43:00.844 --> 43:02.976
And there are no rules.

43:02.978 --> 43:05.112
I mean, you know
the Tolstoy definition of art?

43:05.114 --> 43:06.583
Mmm.

43:08.818 --> 43:11.084
Well, you just have a feeling,

43:11.086 --> 43:12.420
and by means of external signs

43:12.422 --> 43:14.358
you communicate it
to someone else.

43:16.025 --> 43:17.992
That's it.

43:17.994 --> 43:20.894
ANTHONY: So, no reason
to feel intimidated.

43:20.896 --> 43:22.796
I mean, unless you don't
have feelings,

43:22.798 --> 43:24.798
which doesn't seem
to be the case.

43:24.800 --> 43:28.936
I don't see why
you would be intimidated.

43:28.938 --> 43:31.171
Well, people can feel
intimidated.

43:31.173 --> 43:32.273
I don't think that's...

43:32.275 --> 43:33.874
Yeah, I mean,
they can, but...

43:33.876 --> 43:34.909
Perfectly normal.
(MUMBLES INDISTINCTLY)

43:34.911 --> 43:37.144
Not of people who teach.

43:37.146 --> 43:38.345
ANTHONY:
This has got rather warm.

43:38.347 --> 43:39.746
I'm gonna switch it round.

43:39.748 --> 43:41.148
"Those who can't."

43:41.150 --> 43:44.251
Can you swap the warm wine's
heat into this?

43:44.253 --> 43:47.155
- ANTHONY: Shush.
- PATRICK: Thank you.

43:47.157 --> 43:49.791
Thank you for your advice.
It's really...

43:49.793 --> 43:51.758
- It's really helpful.
- LYDIA: Mmm.

43:51.760 --> 43:53.260
You don't seem druggy to me.

43:53.262 --> 43:54.961
No, I'm not.
No, I'm not.

43:54.963 --> 43:56.229
- Interesting.
- LYDIA: Mmm.

43:56.231 --> 44:00.170
So, I'm trying
to work out

44:01.838 --> 44:05.175
where you two
tessellate here.

44:09.813 --> 44:13.014
I'm not good
with euphemism, so...

44:13.016 --> 44:14.418
Sorry, I don't understand.

44:15.719 --> 44:19.887
Okay, so habitual heroin user,

44:19.889 --> 44:22.059
- trainee Rotarian...
- (LYDIA CHUCKLES)

44:23.460 --> 44:26.764
Which is a good look.
I mean it nicely.

44:28.364 --> 44:32.001
How? What? Why? When?

44:38.842 --> 44:40.177
Sorry, I don't...

44:42.244 --> 44:44.378
- You don't even dabble?
- No.

44:44.380 --> 44:47.280
Okay. I mean, I don't.

44:47.282 --> 44:49.483
I feel it's very
mainstream behavior.

44:49.485 --> 44:51.020
I've said to him...

44:53.222 --> 44:54.757
- It's mainstream.
- (SCOFFS)

44:56.525 --> 44:58.094
I actually think, you know...

44:59.295 --> 45:02.496
I mean, it was fine
in the '40s, but...

45:02.498 --> 45:05.133
- ANTHONY: All okay?
- LYDIA: Great.

45:05.135 --> 45:08.302
We are having a charming time.

45:08.304 --> 45:10.474
- ANTHONY: Good.
- PATRICK: I say.

45:12.307 --> 45:14.008
If only you could top up
these olives,

45:14.010 --> 45:15.943
I think we might be able to

45:15.945 --> 45:17.381
get through
the rest of the meal.

45:51.380 --> 45:55.449
This is a scene...
A rehearsal scene.

45:55.451 --> 45:57.450
This is the first
rehearsal he had

45:57.452 --> 46:00.086
with this bunch of
young musicians

46:00.088 --> 46:04.994
that he was going to create
a new band with.

46:06.996 --> 46:10.898
And there he is.
He's quite old.

46:10.900 --> 46:12.532
You can see that they
look a bit nervous,

46:12.534 --> 46:14.270
a bit like you, I think.

46:16.371 --> 46:22.075
Listening to the master
tell them the facts of life.

46:22.077 --> 46:27.384
And also saying
how much it mattered to him,

46:28.184 --> 46:30.184
playing this music.

46:30.186 --> 46:33.887
So it's very parallel,
in my mind,

46:33.889 --> 46:37.858
to what you are beginning
to go through now.

46:37.860 --> 46:39.362
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

47:05.221 --> 47:07.056
Their son's getting married,

47:08.523 --> 47:12.528
and they can't decide whether
they like the girl or not.

47:13.496 --> 47:15.162
ANTHONY: Mmm.

47:15.164 --> 47:17.835
- And he's a doctor.
- Mmm-hmm.

47:19.034 --> 47:20.903
'Cause he's got good hands.

47:26.675 --> 47:29.179
And she's a schoolteacher.

47:32.949 --> 47:35.249
Does she have secrets?

47:35.251 --> 47:37.621
- Of course she does.
- Of course.

47:39.355 --> 47:40.891
Does he?

47:42.125 --> 47:43.460
No.

47:44.360 --> 47:45.429
ANTHONY: Oh.

47:54.704 --> 47:56.874
How would you feel
about going to Venice?

47:57.539 --> 47:59.076
- Venice?
- Mmm-hmm.

48:00.342 --> 48:01.976
I'd love to go.

48:01.978 --> 48:04.045
- I would love that.
- Good.

48:04.047 --> 48:05.615
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

48:09.518 --> 48:11.351
Have you been before?

48:11.353 --> 48:13.387
Yes. Three times.

48:13.389 --> 48:15.389
- Three times?
- Once in summer.

48:15.391 --> 48:17.027
- Twice in winter.
- Mmm-hmm.

48:18.494 --> 48:21.561
Why did you go?
Did you go by yourself?

48:21.563 --> 48:25.668
Uh, no, I went with,
uh, Desiree.

48:28.170 --> 48:31.240
She went mad with jealousy
and jumped in a canal.

48:33.675 --> 48:36.043
Never saw her again.

48:36.045 --> 48:39.713
At least, that was what
her suicide note implied.

48:39.715 --> 48:41.684
I think she ran off
with a gondolier.

48:43.085 --> 48:44.553
No wonder.

48:49.726 --> 48:51.428
So, three girlfriends.

48:52.628 --> 48:54.965
- Yes, all called Desiree.
- Mmm-hmm.

48:55.530 --> 48:57.034
Strange, that.

48:59.735 --> 49:02.036
JULIE: What were their names?

49:02.038 --> 49:03.407
ANTHONY: Miriam,

49:05.240 --> 49:06.576
Caroline

49:07.610 --> 49:09.142
and Angela.

49:09.144 --> 49:11.181
- Angela.
- Mmm.

49:12.414 --> 49:14.280
Angela sang jazz.

49:14.282 --> 49:16.185
They sound unbearable.

49:18.286 --> 49:20.554
(TEARS CHECK)

49:20.556 --> 49:23.356
I suppose they were
frightfully beautiful,

49:23.358 --> 49:26.260
and lots of fun
and rode horses.

49:26.262 --> 49:28.496
If you don't want to know...

49:28.498 --> 49:30.197
- I do want to know
- ...then don't ask.

49:30.199 --> 49:31.335
I do want to know.

49:32.300 --> 49:34.036
Did Miriam
play the cello?

49:35.438 --> 49:36.440
No.

49:37.606 --> 49:39.106
The violin.

49:39.108 --> 49:41.178
No, she wasn't
at all musical.

49:44.213 --> 49:45.983
She wasn't even pretty,
actually.

49:46.581 --> 49:48.548
That's not true.

49:48.550 --> 49:50.353
Well, she had
other qualities.

49:53.456 --> 49:54.458
Like what?

49:56.125 --> 49:57.657
Darling, I can't
tell you in here.

49:57.659 --> 49:58.728
Thank you.

50:00.128 --> 50:01.530
Excuse me?

50:02.798 --> 50:04.634
I'm just playing, Julie.

50:06.568 --> 50:08.202
Stop torturing yourself.

50:08.204 --> 50:09.336
I'm not tort...

50:09.338 --> 50:10.774
Stop inviting me
to torture you.

50:13.476 --> 50:14.478
Ugh!

50:15.478 --> 50:17.144
- Ugh!
- Ugh!

50:17.146 --> 50:18.579
That's exactly
how you make me feel

50:18.581 --> 50:20.050
when you're
being like this.

50:22.251 --> 50:23.483
(PLATES CLINKING)

50:23.485 --> 50:24.487
Thank you.

50:29.791 --> 50:31.694
(ROMANTIC MUSIC PLAYING)

51:05.161 --> 51:07.230
JULIE: That is so beautiful.

51:17.139 --> 51:19.141
(CHURCH BELLS TOLLING)

51:36.858 --> 51:38.525
(CHUCKLING)
I'm not trying that.

51:38.527 --> 51:40.293
No, it's way too...

51:40.295 --> 51:41.597
It's too adventurous.

51:43.199 --> 51:44.201
(CHUCKLING SOFTLY)

51:49.572 --> 51:50.673
Are you packed?

51:52.574 --> 51:53.576
'Course.

51:58.681 --> 52:02.184
Liver? I'm not eating...
I'm not...

52:03.318 --> 52:05.188
No, I'm not interested.

52:08.925 --> 52:11.827
(GROANS) No. No, no.
I'm gonna stick with pasta.

52:12.762 --> 52:14.831
Nice, normal pasta.

52:16.331 --> 52:17.333
Mmm, 'course.

52:18.601 --> 52:20.202
Okay, well, um...

52:20.969 --> 52:22.672
Yeah, I'll see you later.

52:23.639 --> 52:25.706
I... I can't wait.

52:25.708 --> 52:28.474
Hitchcock knew this.
I mean, he would change tack.

52:28.476 --> 52:30.344
I mean, if <i>Psycho,</i> you know,

52:30.346 --> 52:32.746
the scene in... In <i>Psycho,</i>
the shower scene,

52:32.748 --> 52:33.947
- is very much fragments...
- Yeah.

52:33.949 --> 52:35.749
...very much withholding.

52:35.751 --> 52:38.284
But then elsewhere,
he's quite conventional.

52:38.286 --> 52:41.287
So he knows when
to make those adjustments.

52:41.289 --> 52:43.691
Uh, because it is
a process, a growth,

52:43.693 --> 52:46.693
a building
of our sensibilities

52:46.695 --> 52:48.595
and our perceptions,

52:48.597 --> 52:51.465
and we've got to realize that
sometimes we have to change

52:51.467 --> 52:54.300
our approach
as the journey unfolds.

52:54.302 --> 52:57.838
This scene could be related
to that scene in... In <i>Psycho.</i>

52:57.840 --> 52:59.539
So you don't see
the stab wounds.

52:59.541 --> 53:00.773
So you don't see the pain.

53:00.775 --> 53:03.309
- STUDENT: Mmm.
- You just hear it.

53:03.311 --> 53:04.744
You know, you hear
the scream of the woman.

53:04.746 --> 53:05.813
- Yeah.
- You hear the conflict.

53:05.815 --> 53:07.447
- MAN: Yeah.
- So it's quite...

53:07.449 --> 53:08.983
- Could be quite like that.
- MAN: Yes, of course.

53:08.985 --> 53:10.784
And, of course, as, I think,
you know, the books tell us,

53:10.786 --> 53:12.353
- we never do see anything...
- Mmm.

53:12.355 --> 53:13.753
- ...in that shower scene.
- No, you don't see.

53:13.755 --> 53:16.389
Although we have all the...
What appear to be

53:16.391 --> 53:18.626
all the bits and pieces
that we need for the murder,

53:18.628 --> 53:20.894
but then nothing ever happens,
all we see is the knife.

53:20.896 --> 53:24.465
- You just see the knife.
- The knife and the showerhead.

53:24.467 --> 53:27.300
And in this case,
possibly, the conflict,

53:27.302 --> 53:28.969
the noise of the argument,
is the weapon.

53:28.971 --> 53:31.505
- Yes.
- You see the end result,

53:31.507 --> 53:34.874
which could be, in
<i>Psycho,</i> her dead body,

53:34.876 --> 53:36.610
and then,
in this case,

53:36.612 --> 53:39.749
the two broken siblings
at the end.

53:50.525 --> 53:51.627
(JULIE GASPS)

54:00.702 --> 54:01.938
ANTHONY: They've
taken everything.

54:18.621 --> 54:19.990
(OBJECTS CLATTERING)

54:53.088 --> 54:54.724
I'm gonna
call the police.

55:03.065 --> 55:04.601
(ROTARY PHONE DIAL WHIRRING)

55:14.076 --> 55:16.376
(PHONE RECEIVER SLAMS)

55:16.378 --> 55:19.382
- ANTHONY: Argh! God.
- (SLAMS WALL)

55:21.384 --> 55:22.452
Fuck!

55:23.385 --> 55:24.721
(ANTHONY GRUNTS)

55:28.824 --> 55:30.827
I shouldn't have
fucking done that.

55:37.465 --> 55:38.867
(SOBBING)

56:05.561 --> 56:08.431
<i>♪♪ How sad Venice can be</i>

56:09.664 --> 56:12.735
<i>♪♪ When you're on your own</i>

56:13.869 --> 56:17.039
<i>♪♪ How sad Venice can be</i>

56:18.139 --> 56:20.809
<i>♪♪ When you're alone ♪♪</i>

56:44.500 --> 56:46.503
(BELL TOLLING)

56:58.813 --> 57:00.549
- ANTHONY: Thank you.
- BELL BOY: You're welcome.

57:16.998 --> 57:19.867
(BELL BOY SPEAKING ITALIAN)

57:19.869 --> 57:21.204
JULIE: (IN ENGLISH) Thank you.

57:22.505 --> 57:24.707
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

57:53.202 --> 57:55.104
(ANTHONY CLEARING THROAT)

58:02.744 --> 58:05.114
(SOBBING QUIETLY)

58:26.235 --> 58:27.971
ANTHONY: Please tell me
what I've done.

58:32.340 --> 58:33.876
Please, because...

58:37.278 --> 58:39.715
This is punishing,

58:41.349 --> 58:43.952
seeing you like this
and then not knowing why.

58:45.987 --> 58:47.990
(ORCHESTRAL MUSIC PLAYING)

59:09.677 --> 59:11.980
- (MUSIC STOPS)
- (BATON TAPPING)

59:17.753 --> 59:20.289
(OPERATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

59:23.092 --> 59:25.295
(MAN SINGING OPERA)

01:00:26.722 --> 01:00:30.293
I can't go into all this.
It was an emergency.

01:00:34.929 --> 01:00:37.097
- What fucking emergency?
- If I hadn't done that

01:00:37.099 --> 01:00:39.965
on that day, I wouldn't
be here now. I...

01:00:39.967 --> 01:00:44.104
- That's all I can tell you.
- What's that supposed to mean?

01:00:44.106 --> 01:00:46.305
You can't say stuff
like that and then not...

01:00:46.307 --> 01:00:49.208
I appreciate that there are
some things you can't tell me.

01:00:49.210 --> 01:00:51.945
Well, you know, I appreciate
there's things about me

01:00:51.947 --> 01:00:53.345
that you find unacceptable.

01:00:53.347 --> 01:00:55.449
There's things about you
I find unacceptable.

01:00:55.451 --> 01:00:57.083
There's things
about this conversation

01:00:57.085 --> 01:00:59.286
- I find unacceptable.
- The fact that you're a thief.

01:00:59.288 --> 01:01:00.887
We're gonna have
to meet somewhere.

01:01:00.889 --> 01:01:03.826
Anthony, you stole my stuff.
You stole my things.

01:01:05.126 --> 01:01:08.327
Do you understand?
Do you understand that?

01:01:08.329 --> 01:01:10.097
Do you understand
how that would make me feel?

01:01:10.099 --> 01:01:11.965
I didn't think you'd...

01:01:11.967 --> 01:01:15.334
You wouldn't think I...
You didn't think I would mind?

01:01:15.336 --> 01:01:17.373
- Is that what you're saying?
- No. No.

01:01:20.442 --> 01:01:23.112
I knew you'd mind.
That's why I didn't tell you.

01:01:25.012 --> 01:01:29.282
I do what I do so that you can
have the life you're having

01:01:29.284 --> 01:01:31.117
and sleep safe at night,

01:01:31.119 --> 01:01:35.991
and there's not a fucking
car bomb on King's Road.

01:01:38.159 --> 01:01:40.059
Let's laugh about it.
Why not?

01:01:40.061 --> 01:01:41.961
(JULIE SCOFFS)

01:01:41.963 --> 01:01:45.333
I can't...
I can't believe you.

01:01:47.469 --> 01:01:49.903
